                            <comment id="25145" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Wed, 1 Aug 2007 21:13:55 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;We actually had such a suggestion ages ago already... but eventually decided to keep things as-is.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The problem here is that such visibility would apply to the ApplicationContext level (with multiple config files merged into it), so clashes between combined bean definition files would still occur. After all, bean names are unique ids within each ApplicationContext instance, even if that single instance is populated from multiple bean definition files.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Such visibility could only really apply to ApplicationContext hierarchies, which is less useful. And we&apos;d have a semantic problem within the ApplicationContext: Would a getBean call from a bean within the context (e.g. through BeanFactoryAware) see private beans? But a getBean call from a child context wouldn&apos;t? How would we differentiate between those?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Our general solution to this problem is to use fine-grained deployment units, with an internal Spring ApplicationContext sitting inside each unit and only specific services exposed to other units. This is what OSGi provides, of course, hence the nice fit between Spring and OSGi there. The Spring ApplicationContext does not constitute a visibility boundary here; this is handled at the deployment unit (OSGi bundle) level instead.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="25146" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Wed, 1 Aug 2007 21:16:07 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Closed as a duplicate. We&apos;ll track the current status in &lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/browse/SPR-369&quot; title=&quot;Restrict visibility of beans in app context&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;SPR-369&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;SPR-369&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="25157" author="paul4christ79" created="Thu, 2 Aug 2007 01:06:27 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I see the problem posed &lt;img class=&quot;emoticon&quot; src=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/images/icons/emoticons/smile.png&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot; align=&quot;absmiddle&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; border=&quot;0&quot;/&gt; Thanks for the explanation. Is the introduction of OSGi why JavaConfig progress is halted?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
